{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_guava_ver02/data/sn85042792/00332899946/1921020301/0142.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME XXXIX\nBONDS CARRY BV\nLARGE MAZtHH\nTUESDAY\u2019S ELECTIjf RESULTS\nSHOW 446 FOR ONLY\n84 AGAINb\nHIGH SCHOOL TO HE READY NEU FALL\nUnsightly Frame Buildings Will\nThen Be Re noved and the\nGrounds Improved.\nBy an overwhelmingly majority of\n446 to 84 the voters of the city of\nBrookings decided to issue bonds in\nthe sum of $70,000 to complete the\nnew high school building so that it\ncan be occupied next fall, in the spe\ncial election last Tuesday. The few\ndissenting votes cast is considered to\nbe very encouraging and clearly in\ndicative of the general progressive\nthought of the citizens of this public\nspirited community.\nThe building at present is entirely\nenclosed with the exception of win\ndows and presents an appearance\nequal to any public school building\nin the state. The structure has cost\n$166,000 to date which is slightly more\nthan one-half of the estimated cost of\nthe completed building. It is esti\nmated that the building when com\nplete will cost $40,000 less than the\nfigures given by the contractors a year\nago.\nThe money obtained from these\nbonds will be spent in completing the\nmost essential parts of the new build\ning, the class rooms, study rooms, and\nthe gymnasium. The healing, lighting\nand plumbing will be installed. The\nauditorium, corridors and small rooms\nwill remain unfinished until mor-'\nfunds are available.\nThe use of the new building next\nfall will mean a large saving to the\ntaxpayers of the city since it will do\naway with the use of the temporary\nframe buildings which have an ex\ntremely high maintenance cost. As\nsoon as the new building is ready for\nuse the old frame structures will be\nremoved and the grounds will be\ngraded and beautified. It will be a\nvery Important improvement in civic\nbeauty to have those unsightly struc\ntures removed.\nThe vote in Tuesday\u2019s election by\nwards was as follows:\nYes No\nFirst ward 144 32\nSecond ward 132 12\nThird ward 44 14\nFourth ward 126 26\nW. s. 8.-\nEXTENSION CONFERENCE CLOSES\nCounty agents and extension special\nists ot the state closed their week\u2019s\nconference at State college last Fri\nday and returned to their homes well\nphased with the results of the meet\ning and grateful to the hospitality of\nthe citizens of Brookings and the col\nlege. Problems confronting agricul\ntural extension workers were discussed\nand valuable suggestions given to the\nworkers in the tinal sessions held\nThursday and Friday. A program for\nthe coming year was also outlined.\nSchedules of extension specialists in\nagricultural engineering, animal dis\nease work, boys\u2019 and girls\u2019 club work,\ncounty agent work, crops and soils,\ndairying, farm management, market\ning, home demonstration work, insect\ncontrol and plant diseases, livestock\nimprovement, poultry and publicity\nand visual instruction were also con\nsidered. W. F. Kumlein, director of\nextension, and E. W. Hall, county\nagent leader, presided.\nMignon Quaw, the only extension\nspecialist in recreation and social ser\nvice in the country\u2019, addressed the\nworkers on the social side of farm\nbureau work. Miss Quaw is recrea\ntion specialist in Montana.\nIt was decided to discontinue pub\nlication of the Farm Bureau News\nfrom extension headquarters and this\npublication will be put out entirely\nby the county organizations wishing\nto continue it.\nw. s. s.\nCOUNTY PROGRAM OF BUREAU\nThe general board of directors of\nthe Brookings county Farm Bureau,\ncomposed of the chairmen of each\ntownship, have decided upon a big pro\ngram of work to be undertaken by the\norganization this year and have out\nlined the work to the executive com\nmittee who will be charged with the\nduty of carrying out the plans. The\nwork was divided into special branches\nand committees were appointed. The\nvarious chairmen are as follows:\nHogs, Ray Barnett; grain, William\nCrase; cattle, Vernon Walters; pota\ntoes, H. B. McKibben; sheep, Percy\nUllman: organization, Tom Maher;\nroads, L. E. Johnson, Sinai; publicity,\nH. J. Boyts, county agent.\nFrank Telkamp was unable to act\n(Continued on Page 10\u2014Col. 3)\nTHE BROOKINGS\nTOUGH ON CALIFORNIA\nSouth Dakota is thankful this win\nter that it is not afflicted with Cali\nfornia weather, for the weather in\nCalifornia recently has been fierce\nfrom all newspaper accounts. While\nSouth Dakota levels in warm sun\nshine, cloudless skies, and dry weath\ner. California lias a real snowstorm\nand only last Saturday suffered a\nstorm with a gale blowing at I'o mib s\nan hour. Brookings residents who\nwent to California to avoid the ter\nrors of a South Dakota winter have\nthe sympathy of all.\nThe Register received a letter this\nweek from Mrs. J. L. Colgrove who\nis sojourning at Long Beach, contain\ning clippings from the Los Angeles\nTimes telling of the snow storm that\nvisited that city on the same day that\nthe South Dakota society\u2019 held their\nannual picnic in Sycamore grove.\nSnow fell first and was followed by\nrain and hail. There was sufficient\nsnow for the children to have a great\ntime making snowmen. It was esti\nmated that more than 5,000 former\nresidents of South Dakota attended\nthe picnic and more than 200 gallons\nof coffee were consumed. When the\nprogram was nearly over a thunder\nstorm broke loose and the party scat\ntered. The snow struck Los Angeles\nbut did not visit the grove where the\npicnic was held and many of the South\nDakotans were incredulous that it had\nactually snowed in California.\nAn interesting incident is told of\nthe picnic concerning Mrs. Peter Nor\nbeck who happened to be out sight\nseeing that day in a \u201crubber neck\nwagon,\u201d and when the crier an\nnounced, \"On your left is Sycamore\ngrove where the great South Dakota\nsociety composed of thousands of for\nmer citizens are holding their annual\npicnic this afternoon,\u201d Mrs. Norbeck\ncalled to the driver to stop the car,\nexplaining that she was from South\nDakota and was going to quit sight\nseeing for the day to attend the picnic\nand visit with home folks.\nMrs. Colgrove states in her letter\nthat Mrs. Shea Sutton arrived on Sun\nday. January 23, and stood the jour\nney fine.\nCLOSE CONTEST WITH SALEM\nComing to Brookings with a record\nof fourteen victories and but three de\nfeats land reckoned as one of the\nstrongest high school basketball teams\nin the state, Salem high school was\ngiven a hard and fast tussle by the\nBrookings high school team last Fri\nday evening at the armor}\u2019. Up until\nlive minutes before the final whistle\nblew the score was tied 9 to 9. In\nthe last few minutes, however, Salem\ngained strength and scored six points\ngiving them the victory, 15 to 9. The\nlocal high .school team showed a great\nimprov ment in their playing and the r\nremarkable defense against the speedy\nSalem quint was very ocmmendable.\nCoach Armstrong has had difficul'\nwork in turning out a first class bas\nketbail team for the high school and\nin spite of the record of defeats, pros\npects look brighter now and his efforts\nseem likely to be rewarded. Sum\nmary:\nBrookings\u2014 Salem\nHart\u00df. F Wood\nSherman L. FStanga\nLindsey CSessler\nLein R. G Rohlffs\nJohnson L. G Nye\nSubstitutions: Hasle for Lindse\nHalvorson for Hart, Caldwell for Hal\nvorson, Halvorson for Hasle, MeKnight\nfor Sherman, Sahs for Wood, Scar\nlette for Nye.\nField goals: Sahs 3, Sherman 3,\nStanga 1, Scarlet te 1. Rohlffs 1.\nReferee; V.'illadsen.\nw. s. s.\nWALTERS DEFENDS HIMSELF\nFor the first time in the history of\nthe circuit court in this county a man\nhas defended himself in a lawsuit\nwithout the aid of an attorney. W. H.\nWalters acted as his own lawyer in\nthe case tried yesterday before the\ncourt in which the Acme Harvesting\ncompany was sueing him for a sum\nof S4OO, balance due on account Mr.\nWalters lost the case, however, and\njudgment was rendered against him\nfor the sum due. Alexander Alex\nander were the attorneys for the Har\nvesting company.\nThe court today is trying the case\nof L. M. Warne of Sherman vs. U. B\nNelson of Elkton, a suit to recover\nbalance due on the sale of automobile\nsupplies.\nw. s. s.\nORGANIZE AGAINST RUSTLING\nIn an effort to stem the tide of cattle\nrustling and various other kinds of\nlivestock thieving which is sweeping\nthe western part of the state, an or\nganization to be known as the Tri-\nState Live Stock Protective associa\ntion, has been perfected with a charter\nmembership of approximately 1,501. M.\nJ. Smiley was elected president and S.\nG. Mortimer treasurer.\nw. s. s\nBROOKINGS, SOUTH DAKOTA. FEBRUARY 3. 1921\nMAKE HISTORY AT\nFARM CONVENTION\nSTATE FARM BUREAU FEDERA\nTION CLOSES IMPORTANT\nBUSINESS HERE\nMAKE STATEMENT OF THEIR POLICIES\nWant Protective Tariff, Changes in\nIncome Tax Law and Vote\nAgainst Nolan Bill.\nThe greatest and most important\nbusiness gathering of the farmers ever\nheld in South Dakota was held in this\ncity last week. While the average\ncitizen might have been unaware of\nit, the farmer delegates of the South\nDakota Farm Buteau Federation were\nmaking history in the agricultural\nprogress of the state at their meet\nings at State college. The final busi\nness session of the annual state con\nvention was held last Thursday and\nthe delegates left that night and the\nfollowing day for their homes.\nW. S. Hill of Hanson county, was\nelected president of the South Da\nkota Farm Bureau Federation by a\nunanimous vote at the final session.\nThe following were elected as mem\nbers oi the board of directors: First\ncongressional district, S. Thomp\nson, Minnehaha county, two-year term,\nand John Odland of Turner county,\none year. Second congressional dis\ntrict, 11. K. Dubach, lark county, two\nyear term, and W. H. Davis, Spink\ncounty, one year. Third congressional\ndistrict, F. L. Kelso, Fall River coun\nty. two-year term, and Edgar Wat\nwood, Haakon county, one year. The\nfirst board meeting was called by\nPresident Hill last Monday.\nThe federation enlarged its program\nof work to cover marketing of grain,\nlivestock, wool, seed and potatoes;\ncrop and livestock statistics; organiza\ntion work, executive department, leg\nislation, legal investigations, news ser\nvice and advertising, general office\nexpense and emergency needs.\nSpecial permanent committees will\nbe formed to represent each if the\nfive marketing divisions and others,\nlooking forward toward the organza\ntion of a marketing bureau and tin\nemployment of necessary help. To\nhelp meet the increased expense, the\nconvention raised the membership fee\ndue to the state office from $1.50, as\nat present, to $5 per member per year.\n\u2019The South Dakota Farm Bureau\nfederation went on record as favoring\nthe French truth in-fabric bill, a bill\nto localize collective bargaining by\nfarmers: a revision of the tariff u\nward on farm products especially dur\ning Hit* present adjustment period:\nthe enactment of such emergency 1>\nislation as will prevent the annihila\ntion of the wool growing industry: tlm\nenactment of a protective tariff to\nstriding the importation of foreign\nsugar and its products; changes in tin\nnational income tax law such that\nthe profit on land ho taxed on the ba i\nof the number of years in which tlii\nprofit accrued, instead of taxing the\naccumulated profit as though it had\nbeen made in the year of sale.\nThe federation convention also ex\npressed itself opposed to the Nolan\nbill now before congress which pro\nvides for a tax of one per cent on all\nland values above SIO,OOO.\nMrs. R. N. Van Winkle of Brown\ncounty, presented what she believed\nto be women\u2019s part in the farm bu\nreau. She said woman's first interest\nin the welfare of the home and the\ncommunity, in fact that the men are\ndeveloping the farm bureau in order\nto make the home what it should ho.\nWomen are progressive, she asserted,\nand are ready at all times to take\nup now ideas for home and farm im\nprovement. The farm boys and girls\nwho are sent to college should ho pro\nvided with good homes in which to\nlive upon their return, else they will\nbo dissatisfied with farm life.\nSTATE OF TRADE\nThe state of trade over the country\nas reported by Bradstreet\u2019s for la\nweek continued to show Improvenu-n\u2019\nMore lines of trade and markets re\nport better feeling or increased buy\nIng. Small and often is the phrase\nbest describing buying. Some rece\nsions In some lines balanced by ad\nvances in others. Reports from east\nand west best, but southern centers\nslightly improved. current in\nIron and steel production. Buying\nslow. Lower wages talked of in steel\nand railway operation. Large esti\nmates of unemployment not Indica\ntive in all centers. Commodity prices\nstill tend downward. Breadstuffs, cot\nton and live animals lower. Security\nmarkets without much change. Ex\nchange higher, led by sterling. Fail\nures fewer.\n-W. S. 8.\nHIOHO-ELECTRIC\nFIGHT WARMS UP\nMOBRIDGE BOOSTERS INTRODUCE\nBILL TO ACCEPT REPORT\nOF COMMISSION\nLEGISLATURE STILL FAVORS ECONOMY\nDick R.chards Starts Things Again\nWith His Legal Merit Bill\nTo Buy Booze.\nThe boosters for the hydro-electric\ns tvs at Mobridge and at Mulehead\nare yet on hand pushing their various\n<la in.''. The Mobridge people have\nintroduced a bill which merely ac\ncepts the report of the engineers and\nof the hydro-electric commission and\nthe first test will come on this. They\nclaim that they are not asking for\nany appropriation, nor for any action\nat this time, but want only an accept\nance of the reports of the governing\nand engineering bodies so far in con\ntrol of the probabilities of hydro\nelectric development of the big river.\nThe vote on this will likely be a test\nof what is to Im l expected. Their bill\nhas the advantage that so long as it\ndoes not carry an appropriation it can\nbe adopted by a majority vote of each\nhouse The Mulehead people have\nnot yet presented their bill which\ncalls for a location at the southern\npoint, but they can be counted on to\nge- busy when they think the proper\ntime has arrived. Both forces have\nconcluded that they need not look for\n\nany action at this session which would\ncaJl for an appropriation, and if any-\nthing is enacted it will be along the\nlines laid down in the \u201cMobridge\u201d\nbill, but that does not mean that their\nparticular bill will go through.\nThe one proposition which will no\ndoubt cause more discussion than any\nother one thing which has been intro\nduced since the recess, is the bill by\nOhlman, with a title longer than the\naverage* bill, which is one of the pet\nideas of R. O. Richards, and which at-\ntempts to set up a standard of morals\nfor citizenship privileges. The title\n..\u2019(\u2022\u2019designated as an act to standardize i\nthe citizenship to individual responsi\nbility under a legal merit system to\nstimulate morality as a basis for tem\nperance, with many more words fol\nlowing. In brief the bill attempts tq\nfix a legal standard of morals, and\nthe man who can meet the required\ntest shall be allowed to buy and drink\n'\u2022cer and wine, and to vote. If he can\u2019t\nnme up to the tandard he is to be\ndeprived of both these rights. Among\nether things which make a citizen\n\u201cimmoral\u201d and not. entitled to the\nhove privileges being a deadbeat, a\n>afer, a liar, failure to support his\n'amily, drunkenness, or general im\norality. Of conviction of any of\nthese offenses his certificate to drink\nind vote is t ken away from him. in\ndefining the drUks which may be al\niwed, moonshine and home brew is\nlaced under 'he ban, and any who\nuse this are cut out from the privi\nleges which go with the moral cor\nticate which must be secured from\nhe court. A companion bill with this\nomlng from the same source is one\ni abolish the office \"f state sheriff.\nThe members have returned from\nheir trip home imbued to even a\nreater extent than that which pr<-\nvaded the legislative atmosphere be-1\n'ore the vacation, that it is up to them\nto see that there is no appropriation\nwhich is not absolutely necessary to\ncarry on the affairs of the state, and\nthis was evidently especially im\npressed on the members generally by\ntheir constituents, if their talk since\ntheir return is any indication of what\nthey learned.\nThe members have hardly got back\nto normal as yet since the recess, but\nby the beginning of the week they\nwill get down to routine again, as\npractically all the absent ones will b<\nback by that time. Several members\nire out on investigation work outlined\nfor them by the session before re\ncess, and their work will likely b'*\ncleared up soon. Gill of Brookings,\nBelk of Codington, and* VanOrnum of\nSpink are on the committee sent to\nSioux Falls to investigate the twine\nsituation at the penitentiary and that\nwill likely take them several days.\nLittle now legislation was start' d by\n\u2022he returned members up to the end\nof the week, and outside of the freak\nbills presented, the ones which are\nof the most, general interest Is one\nto cut the compulsory features from\nthe state hail insurance act. The hail\ndepartment takes the position that if\nthis feature is elminated, the w\u2019hole\nlaw should be repealed as the states\nwhich tried an optional law all admit\nfailure, and the option states of Okla\nhoma, Nebraska and Montana have\nasked for copies of the hall law in\nthis state on which to base a new plan.\nJuet what action will be taken is to\n(Continued on Page s\u2014Col, 4)\nREGISTE\nBISHOP MITCHELL PLEASES ALL\n\nB shop Charles Bayard Mitchell of\nSi. Paul. was a distinguished visitor\nin Brookings this week and pleased\nlar e audiences at the Metohdlst\nEp -m opal church, at State college, and\naddresed the Rotarv club at their\nnoon day luncheon on Monday. Ills\nprincipal lecture, \u201cThe Prize Taker,\"\nwas delivered Monday t veiling at the\nMethodist church to an audience of\nfive hundred jieisons. His subject be\nfore the Rotary club was \u201cThe Art of\nHuman Approach.\" Ills lectures were\nfull of force, wisdom, and dear think\ning delivered in an interesting style\nthat made a universal appeal.\nPreceding the lecture Monday even\ning, Donald Farley, organist at the\nMethodist church, offered a short re\ncital. \"A man must have aim,\u201d said\nBishop Mitchell. \u201cThe trouble with\nmost people is that they lack objec\ntive and follow the line of least re\ns.steme. A captain at sea knows\nwhere he is going. Success in life is\na question of will. Our eternal des\ntiny hinges in our will. Be the cre\nator of your circumstances, not the\ncreature of your circumstances.\n\u201cWhile your will power is domiriant,\nthere are two things you cannot con\ntrol, a\u2019neestry and place of birth. You\ncan make out of your life what you\nwant to. Il was the soul of Patrick\nHenry that made him great\u2014not his\nsurroundings. Concentrate all your\npowers towards one single object and\nyou will win the prize.\n\"Modern civilization is the sum and\nsubstance of men who have done one\nthing and done that well. Let a man\nlook himself over, turn himself about,\nstudy himself, and he will find some\none thing he can do and do better,\nor as well as any one else.\n\u201cDon\u2019t be narrow. Too many peo\nple now can look through a keyhole\nwith both eyes. Michael Angelo was\nthe greatest figure in the Italian\nrennaissance because he did things on\na colossal scale. He was not narrow.\nMake your life ample.\n\u201cMost people are greedy and they\ngrab at everything and get nothing.\nGrab at one thing. Don\u2019t take a short\ncut toward making money. If you are\ngoing to start at the bottom toward\nsuccess, you must say goodbye to\nmoney and to leisure.\n\u201cWe may all take life\u2019s highest\nprize, hut there are a thousand things\nwe must not do, a thousand words we\nmust not say, and a thousand places\nwe must not go, we have too much at\nstake. Life's highest prize is charac\nter.\u201d\nBishop Mitchell was for nine years\npastor of St. James\u2019s church, Chicago,\nand served Hennepin Avenue church,\nMinneapolis, and First church, Cleve\nland. preceding his elevation to the\nepiscopacy His residential area in\ncludes the states of South Dakota,\nMinnesota and Wisconsin.\nHe represents his church at the\nEacumenical conference of Methodism\nt London next sumer\nW. S. S,-\nALUMNI MEET FAR AWAY\nIn the far-off state of Washington,\na group of State college graduates and\nformer students renewed acquaint\nance and talked over old times at a\nspecial dinner held at the Palace ho\ntel in Pullman, Wash., on Monday\nevening, January 17. No matter whet e\nState college alumni are they always\nfee] the urge to keep up their old col\nlege associations.\n'Those present were: A B. Crane,\n\u20199l, drainage specialist extension ser\nvice, and Mrs. Harriet (Dibble) Stow,\n\u20199t. home demonstration agent, Snoho\nmish county, of Everett, Wash.; Miss\nMinnie Lawrence, \u201999, home manage\nment specialist: W. W. Underwood,\nassistant county agent leader, and\nE E. Onstlne, a student at Washing\nton State college of Pullman, Wash\nand Mrs. Inez (Armstrong) Hunt,\nhome demonstration agent of Yakima,\nWash.\nTwenty five thousand pounds of half\nblood staple wool and 125.000 pounds\nof half blood clothing wool was sold\nout of the Minnesota-Dakota grade by\nthe National Wool Warehouse and\nStorage company of Chicago, accord\ning to advices just received by J. C.\nHolmes, livestock specialist at State\ncollege and secretary\u2019 of the South\nDakota Sheep and Wool Growers* as\nsociation. The two lots were sold at\n29 cents and 27 cents per pound, re\nspectively. This means that perhaps\none-tenth of South Dakota\u2019s east of\nthe river wool was included in this\nsale. This is considered a very close\nprice, but as it is a dark w\u2019ool and\nthe demand is not so great the price is\nconsidered fairly satisfactory.\nw. s. s.\nBoys and girls under 18 years of\nage will not be permitted tc attend\npublic dances in Huron if an ordi\nnance suggested by prominent men\nand women of Huron passes the city\ncouncil. A curfew ordinance will also\nbe submitted.\nw. s. s.-\nHALF MILLION POUNDS SOLD\nGERMANS ASSERT\nTHEY CAN\u2019T FA!\nREFUSE TO NEGOTIATE ON THE\nBASIS OF PROPOSALS\nOF THE ALLIES\nSAY THAT TERMS WOULD PRODUCE CHAOS\nTerms Provide Payment on Increasing\nScale According to Return\nof Prosperity.\nFresh trouble is being started with\nGermany over the payment of the in\ndemnity asked by the Allies and the\nsituation at the present time is very\ntense. Dr. Walter Simons, the foreign\nminister, says that Germany cannot\npay the huge amount asked. In a\nspeech before the German relchstag\nhe delared that Germany would refuse\nto negotiate on the basis of the entente\ndecisions regarding reparations and\nformulate counter proposals. His po\nsition was supported by all the party\nleaders except the communists who\nheckled and jeered him when he con\ncluded speaking.\nThe proposed scheme provides for\nthe payment of annuities on a sliding\nscale of from 2,000,000,000 to 6,000,000,-\n(100 gold marks over a period of forty\ntwo years and also a per cent\nad valorem tax on German exports so\nthat her creditors will be paid accord\ning to Germany\u2019s Increasing prosperity.\nMadness,\u201d is the term leaders of\nthe reichstag used in discussing the\nreparation conditions. Foreign Minis\nter Simons declared the execution of\nthe terms would \u201cproduce chaos, not\nonly in Germany, but throughout cen\ntral Europe, as the bankruptcy of Ger\nmany would also bankrupt part of Ger\nmany\u2019s war creditors, among whom is\nFrance.\u201d\n\"It is greatly to be deplored,\u201d he\ncontinued, \u201cthat the great American\nnation was only a bystander during\nthe negotiations concerning repara\ntions at Paris. The settlement of this\nquestion determines the fate of the\nworld\u2019s economics and of world cul\nture.\u201d\nw. s. s.\nNORMALITES EASILY DOWNED\nThe second string men on the State\ncollege basketball squad were enough\nto defeat any contentions the Northern\nNormal of Aberdeen may have had\nfor the winning of state basketball\nhonors when the two teajns clashed\nat the armory last Saturday evening.\nThe final score was 36 to 22 in favor\nof State. Coach west started the\ngame with the regular line-up but\nthey ran away with things so fast\nthat the game was scarcely interest\ning so in a few minutes the second\nDam was substituted. The score at\nthe end of the first half was 24 to 9\nin favor of State, which tells fairly\naccurately the ease with which the\nregulars gathered in the points in the\nfew minutes which they played. After\nthe substitution the visitors were able\nto battle the second team on even\nterms for the rest of the game, A\nfeature of the game was the large\nnumber of fouls called on players of\nboth teams. Coach West\u2019s quint was\nworking as a smooth unit and dis\nplayed a machine like skill and preci\nsion that places State college as the\nforemost contender for state honors\nthis year. It is a stellar team without\nindividual stars, which is the hardest\nkind of a basketball team to beat.\nSchutte at center with his fast floor\nwork was easily the star of the Nor\nmal team.\nThe coach has been devoting his\ntime this week to whipping the team\ninto the best shape possible for the\ngames tonight and tomorrow\u2019 night at\nVermillion against State\u2019s greatest\nrival, the University of South Dakota.\nTen men have been picked to make\nthe trip. The Coyottes have been\nplaying a strong game this season\nalthough they have suffered defeat at\nthe hands of Nebraska university and\nCreighton university. Nothing from\ncomparative scores yields any import\nant information as to their strength,\nbut there Is no doubt whatever in the\nState college camp hut that State will\nsquare up for the defeat at football\nlast fall.\nThe line-up for last Saturday\u2019s game\nis as follows:\nState Normal\u2014\nCarey R. F Bachman\nJohnson L. F Helnzelman\nThune C Schutte\nWilladsen L. G Wortman\nPatterson L.G Cooper\nSubstitutes: Nelson for Carey;\nRoberts for Johnson; Towers for\nThune; Lee for Willadsen; Bumside\nfor Nelson; Anderson for Cooper.\nField goals: Carey 3, Johnson 1,\nRoberts 1, Thune 3, Towers 2, Willad\nsen 2, Bumside 1, Bachman 1, Schutte\n3, Wortman 1, Nelson 1, Helnselman 1.\nFoul goals: Carey 8, Towan t,\nSchutte 8, Heinselman 1.\nNUMBER 39\n''fi\ny","height":"35716","width":"25888"}}
